the neighboring galaxies but we have already accumulated quite a trove of wisdom and almost all of them are recorded in books.\n\nAlmost.\n\n<b>Have real-life adventures.</b> Travel when and where you can. Take unknown paths. Do things without always knowing how they''ll turn out. This is how you''ll accumulate wisdom for yourself. You''ll surely be missing out a lot if you don''t read books but never ever forget that your life is one huge book-in-the-works as well and it will be such a shame to look back one day, realizing that your book is empty or well-written but unread.\n\n<b>Make mistakes.</b> Waste your time. You''ll thank yourself for it. If that book you are writing isn''t full of erasures you are most probably not trying out a lot of things. Don''t follow tried-and-tested recipes. That is not how you''ll learn.\n\n<b>Be aware of what you don''t know.</b> And I assure you this will save your skin. And the skin of the people tossed with you in this adventure. Being aware of what you don''t know will help you make sense of your mistakes. You will be better prepared next time. Hallelujah to the things we don''t know.\n\nAnd lastly,\n\n<b>Do not listen to every advice thrown your way.</b> I have come to accept that life, unlike research, does not require a theoretical framework for you to move forward. All you need is some nerve and, believe you me, you will be surprised how often this Universe/Fate/Destiny/Karma/God rewards raw nerve. Not always, but more often than what other people will have you believe. It is alright to just make things up as you go. No one will take it against you.', 'For What It''s Worth', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '19-revision', '', '', '2012-12-22 08:32:16', '2012-12-22 08:32:16', '', 19, 'http://localhost/skytreader.net/19-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
